PCE price index (Fed's favored inflation gauge) fell to just +0.3% in Q1, down from +2.2% in Q1. Core PCE fell to +0.9%, down from +1.8%.
Housing was the only real negative in today's preliminary US Q2 GDP report, with everything else moderately positive.
US Q2 GDP +2.6% = +1.9 Consumption +0.6 Business Investment +0 Inventories -0.3 Housing +0.1 Government Spending +0.2 Net Exports.
Interesting to note growth in goods exports slowed from +10.8% in Q1 to +2.8% in Q2, while service exports accelerated from +1.0% to +6.5%.
Export growth slowed from +7.3% in Q1 to +4.1% in Q2, while imports slowed from +4.3% to +2.1%. Smaller trade gap added +0.2 points to GDP.
Government spending rose +0.7% in Q2, driven by +5.2% boost in defense spending, adding +0.1 point to GDP growth.
Residential investment fell -6.8% in Q2, after surging +11.1% in Q1, and subtracted -0.3 points from GDP growth as housing market cooled.
Inventories were neutral in Q2, neither adding nor subtracting to GDP growth, after retrenchment shaved -1.5 points off Q1 GDP growth.
Q1's +7.2% surge in fixed business investment moderated to a still-respectable +5.2% in Q2, adding +0.6 points to GDP growth.
Consumption growth rebounded from a low of +1.2% in Q1 to +2.8% in Q2, adding +1.9 points to GDP growth (more in line with Q3 and Q4 2016).
Preliminary US GDP growth for Q2 was +2.6% - pretty much as expected.
